05015nam a22008415i 9780674735941DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152014mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013946091  a(OCoLC)1029812596  a(OCoLC)1032686646  a(OCoLC)1037981311  a(OCoLC)1041971226  a(OCoLC)1046613860  a(OCoLC)1046997476  a(OCoLC)979590103  a97806747359417 a10.4159/harvard.97806747359412doi  a(DE-B1597)427408  a(OCoLC)897599454  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aD843b.M265 2015eb 7aHIS0270202bisacsh04a909.82/52231 aHajimu, Masuda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCold War Crucible :bThe Korean Conflict and the Postwar World /cMasuda Hajimu. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2015] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (358 p.) :b34 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: What Was the Cold War? -- tI. THE REPERCUSSIONS -- tII. THE SOCIAL -- tIII. THE SIMULTANEITY -- tEpilogue: The Cold War as Social Politics -- tNotes -- tArchives Consulted -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe end of World War II did not mean the arrival of peace. The major powers faced social upheaval at home, while anticolonial wars erupted around the world. American-Soviet relations grew chilly, but the meaning of the rivalry remained disputable. Cold War Crucible reveals the Korean War as the catalyst for a new postwar order. The conflict led people to believe in the Cold War as a dangerous reality, a belief that would define the fears of two generations. In the international arena, North Korea’s aggression was widely interpreted as the beginning of World War III. At the domestic level, the conflict generated a wartime logic that created dividing lines between “us” and “them,” precipitating waves of social purges to stifle dissent. The United States allowed McCarthyism to take root; Britain launched anti-labor initiatives; Japan conducted its Red Purge; and China cracked down on counterrevolutionaries. These attempts to restore domestic tranquility were not a product of the Cold War, Masuda Hajimu shows, but driving forces in creating a mindset for it. Alarmed by the idea of enemies from within and faced with the notion of a bipolar conflict that could quickly go from chilly to nuclear, ordinary people and policymakers created a fantasy of a Cold War world in which global and domestic order was paramount. In discovering how policymaking and popular opinion combined to establish and propagate the new postwar reality, Cold War Crucible offers a history that reorients our understanding of what the Cold War really was.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCold War. 0aKorean War, 1950-1953xInfluence. 0aWorld politicsy1945-1989. 7aHISTORY / Military / Korean War.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2015z9783110438635oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067473594140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674735941423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674735941.jpg  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS